</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF8B3953EBD2C5F8FD71583E" blockId="37.[227,1437,715,777]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
The otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF8B3953EAA6C5FFFDCC59D3" authorityName="Nolf &amp; Stringer" authorityYear="2003" box="[407,563,716,741]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="yazooensis">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8B3953EAA6C5FFFDCC59D3" box="[407,563,716,741]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">P. yazooensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear to be more pointed and acuminate at their posterior end, compared to those of other congeneric species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
